1
00:00:05,714 --> 00:00:08,934
<i>TYSON".
We pulled the stars from the skies...</i>

2
00:00:11,929 --> 00:00:14,682
<i>...and brought them down to Earth.</i>

3
00:00:25,359 --> 00:00:27,737
<i>But at what cost?</i>

4
00:00:28,111 --> 00:00:31,115
<i>When we turned on all these lights...</i>

5
00:00:31,281 --> 00:00:33,750
<i>...we lost something precious.</i>

6
00:00:34,785 --> 00:00:36,128
The stars.

7
00:02:36,406 --> 00:02:40,161
TYSON: A long time ago,
in a world lit only by fire...

8
00:02:40,327 --> 00:02:43,627
...our relationship with the stars
was far more...

9
00:02:44,164 --> 00:02:46,087
...personal.

10
00:02:46,249 --> 00:02:47,751
For thousands of generations...

11
00:02:47,918 --> 00:02:50,842
<i>...we watched the stars
as if our lives depended on it.</i>

12
00:02:51,004 --> 00:02:52,927
<i>Because they did.</i>

13
00:02:54,675 --> 00:02:57,554
We humans were not the biggest,
the strongest...

14
00:02:57,719 --> 00:03:00,438
...nor the fastest of all the animals
we competed against.

15
00:03:00,597 --> 00:03:04,352
But we did have one thing going for us:
our intelligence.

16
00:03:04,518 --> 00:03:08,443
One aspect of that was a genius
for pattern recognition.

17
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:10,699
Night after night, we watched the stars.

18
00:03:11,274 --> 00:03:14,904
And over time, our ancestors noticed
that the motions of the stars...

19
00:03:15,070 --> 00:03:18,700
...across the nights of the year
foretold changes on Earth...

20
00:03:18,865 --> 00:03:21,789
...that threatened or enhanced
our chances for survival.

21
00:03:21,952 --> 00:03:26,503
In a time when our imaginations were the
only stage where stories came to life...

22
00:03:26,665 --> 00:03:30,715
...before there were movies or TVs
or electronic devices of any kind...

23
00:03:30,877 --> 00:03:35,758
...every human culture connected the dots
to form their own pictures.

24
00:03:37,634 --> 00:03:40,934
<i>These images became the illustrations
of a storybook...</i>

25
00:03:41,096 --> 00:03:44,475
<i>...that, on a deeper level,
was also a survival manual.</i>

26
00:03:44,641 --> 00:03:49,772
<i>The names and personalities of the gods,
heroes, farm animals or familiar objects...</i>

27
00:03:49,938 --> 00:03:51,690
<i>...varied from culture to culture.</i>

28
00:03:51,857 --> 00:03:56,033
<i>But there was one particularly gorgeous
group of stars...</i>

29
00:03:56,987 --> 00:04:02,289
<i>...known to the ancient Greeks
and to us today as the Pleiades...</i>

30
00:04:02,451 --> 00:04:05,830
<i>...a star cluster formed
about a hundred million years ago.</i>

31
00:04:05,996 --> 00:04:09,500
<i>Each of them is some 40 times brighter
than our sun.</i>

32
00:04:09,666 --> 00:04:16,094
<i>And Alcyone, the most luminous,
outshines our sun a thousand times.</i>

33
00:04:16,256 --> 00:04:19,009
<i>For ages, the Pleiades
have been used as an eye test...</i>

34
00:04:19,176 --> 00:04:21,929
<i>...for people all over the world.</i>

35
00:04:22,095 --> 00:04:26,020
<i>If you could see at least six of them,
you were considered normal.</i>

36
00:04:26,183 --> 00:04:28,026
<i>If you saw more than seven...</i>

37
00:04:28,185 --> 00:04:31,780
<i>...you were an ideal candidate
for a warrior or scout.</i>

38
00:04:31,938 --> 00:04:34,691
<i>Among the ancient Celts and Druids
of the British isles...</i>

39
00:04:34,858 --> 00:04:38,283
<i>...the Pleiades were believed
to have a haunting significance.</i>

40
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:42,370
<i>On the night of the year that they reach
the highest point in the sky at midnight...</i>

41
00:04:42,532 --> 00:04:45,957
<i>...the spirits of the dead
were thought to wander the earth.</i>

42
00:04:46,119 --> 00:04:50,590
<i>This is believed to be the origin
of the holiday once known as Samhain...</i>

43
00:04:50,749 --> 00:04:52,547
<i>...now called Halloween.</i>

44
00:04:52,709 --> 00:04:55,883
<i>All over the earth,
our ancestors told wonderful stories...</i>

45
00:04:56,046 --> 00:05:00,176
<i>...to explain how the Pleiades came
to be in the sky.</i>

46
00:05:00,342 --> 00:05:05,064
For the Kiowa people of North America,
it happened something like this.

47
00:05:07,641 --> 00:05:09,393
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

48
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:17,026
<i>TYSON: Long, long ago, some young women
snuck away from their campsite...</i>

49
00:05:17,192 --> 00:05:20,571
<i>...to dance freely beneath the stars.</i>

50
00:05:32,082 --> 00:05:33,174
[ROARS]

51
00:05:33,333 --> 00:05:35,210
[WOMEN SCREAMING]

52
00:05:53,603 --> 00:05:55,276
Rock, save us.

53
00:05:55,438 --> 00:05:58,112
Rock, take pity on us.

54
00:05:58,942 --> 00:06:02,913
<i>TYSON".
The rock heard their cries and grew taller.</i>

55
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:13,090
<i>Until it became what is today known
as the Devils Tower.</i>

56
00:06:17,794 --> 00:06:21,890
<i>The maidens were transformed
into the stars of the Pleiades...</i>

57
00:06:22,048 --> 00:06:26,053
<i>...which may be seen hanging
above the tower in midwinter.</i>

58
00:06:27,304 --> 00:06:31,730
<i>The ancient Greeks also saw
those seven jewels as seven maidens...</i>

59
00:06:31,892 --> 00:06:34,816
<i>...the seven daughters of Atlas...</i>

60
00:06:35,854 --> 00:06:40,075
<i>...pursued not by bears,
but by Orion the hunter...</i>

61
00:06:40,233 --> 00:06:43,863
<i>...who spied them
when he was out walking one day.</i>

62
00:06:52,162 --> 00:06:55,757
<i>Orion became mad with desire.</i>

63
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:57,213
[CHUCKLES]

64
00:06:57,375 --> 00:06:58,672
[WOMEN GASPING]

65
00:07:02,339 --> 00:07:06,014
<i>TYSON". For seven years, he
chased them relentlessly.</i>

66
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:10,226
<i>Exhausted...
Zeus,</i> help <i>us.</i>

67
00:07:10,388 --> 00:07:13,517
<i>TYSON".
...they prayed to Zeus for deliverance.</i>

68
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:19,065
<i>Zeus, the king of the gods,
felt sorry for them...</i>

69
00:07:19,689 --> 00:07:24,536
<i>...and transformed those seven maidens
into the Pleiades.</i>

70
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:36,669
But the gods are, if anything, capricious.

71
00:07:36,831 --> 00:07:39,835
When Orion was killed
by the sting of a scorpion...

72
00:07:40,001 --> 00:07:41,469
...Zeus placed him in the sky...

73
00:07:41,628 --> 00:07:45,178
...where he could resume his pursuit
of the seven gorgeous sisters.

74
00:07:45,340 --> 00:07:48,890
Our ancestors,
they wove brilliantly imaginative stories.

75
00:07:49,052 --> 00:07:52,477
But they can bring us no closer
to the stars than our dreams.

76
00:07:52,639 --> 00:07:54,562
It took yet another few thousand years...

77
00:07:54,724 --> 00:07:57,898
...until three brilliant scientists
unlocked the secrets...

78
00:07:58,061 --> 00:08:00,564
...of the true lives of the stars.

79
00:08:13,743 --> 00:08:18,590
TYSON:
<i>In 1901, Harvard was</i> a <i>man's world.</i>

80
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:21,422
<i>But an astronomer
named Edward Charles Pickering...</i>

81
00:08:21,584 --> 00:08:23,678
<i>...broke that rule.</i>

82
00:08:25,839 --> 00:08:28,592
Old Pickering's office
is just down the hallway.

83
00:08:28,758 --> 00:08:34,765
And that door over there leads to the room
where he keeps his computers.

84
00:08:35,432 --> 00:08:37,776
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

85
00:08:45,233 --> 00:08:47,827
We're supposed
to call those women "computers"...

86
00:08:47,986 --> 00:08:51,786
...but, uh, I've heard more than one fellow
refer to those gals...

87
00:08:51,948 --> 00:08:54,792
...as "Pickering's Harem."
MEN: Ha-ha-ha.

88
00:08:54,951 --> 00:08:59,752
<i>TYSON". Pickering assembled a team of women
to map and classify the types of stars.</i>

89
00:09:00,457 --> 00:09:03,131
<i>One of them provided the key
to our understanding...</i>

90
00:09:03,293 --> 00:09:05,011
<i>...of the substance of the stars.</i>

91
00:09:05,170 --> 00:09:10,643
<i>And another devised a way for us
to calculate the size of the universe.</i>

92
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:14,475
For some reason, you've probably
never heard of either of them.

93
00:09:15,055 --> 00:09:16,807
Wonder why.

94
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:22,150
<i>That's Annie Jump Cannon,
the leader of the team.</i>

95
00:09:22,312 --> 00:09:27,819
<i>Before she was through,
she cataloged a quarter of a million stars.</i>

96
00:09:28,985 --> 00:09:31,659
Number 11 is a B7.

97
00:09:31,821 --> 00:09:34,665
That's Alcyone in the Pleiades.

98
00:09:34,824 --> 00:09:37,452
<i>TYSON: Cannon lost her hearing
during a bout of scarlet fever...</i>

99
00:09:37,619 --> 00:09:38,996
<i>...when she was a young woman.</i>

100
00:09:39,162 --> 00:09:41,756
Number 12 is a B6.

101
00:09:41,915 --> 00:09:44,168
<i>TYSON".
That's Henrietta Swan Leavitt.</i>

102
00:09:44,334 --> 00:09:45,586
<i>She's also deaf.</i>

103
00:09:45,752 --> 00:09:48,301
<i>And she's the other great scientist
in the room.</i>

104
00:09:48,463 --> 00:09:53,094
<i>Leavitt discovered the law that astronomers
still use more than a century later...</i>

105
00:09:53,259 --> 00:09:58,857
<i>...to measure the distances to the stars
and the size of the cosmos itself.</i>

106
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:02,899
<i>Annie Jump Cannon
sent out a Christmas card explaining...</i>

107
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:06,110
<i>...what she and her sisters
were actually doing.</i>

108
00:10:06,272 --> 00:10:07,899
<i>The light from a star is allowed...</i>

109
00:10:08,066 --> 00:10:11,661
<i>...to fall through a prism placed
in the telescope, she wrote.</i>

110
00:10:11,820 --> 00:10:17,748
<i>Thus magnified, the starlight is split up
into a band showing its component colors...</i>

111
00:10:17,909 --> 00:10:21,834
<i>...the red rays going to one end
and the violet to the other.</i>

112
00:10:21,996 --> 00:10:24,294
<i>This is the spectrum of the star.</i>

113
00:10:24,457 --> 00:10:27,677
<i>It shows the presence of fine, dark lines.</i>

114
00:10:27,836 --> 00:10:32,012
<i>By comparing them with lines given
by glowing substances in the laboratory...</i>

115
00:10:32,173 --> 00:10:36,098
<i>...we can determine that the same elements
familiar to us on the Earth...</i>

116
00:10:36,261 --> 00:10:40,061
<i>...also exist in the outermost star.</i>

117
00:10:49,524 --> 00:10:53,495
This is plate number 123588.

118
00:10:59,242 --> 00:11:03,668
Number one at this plate
is a B-type star.

119
00:11:06,082 --> 00:11:08,710
Make that a B2.

120
00:11:11,421 --> 00:11:14,925
<i>TYSON: It took Cannon decades
to classify the spectral character...</i>

121
00:11:15,091 --> 00:11:17,185
<i>...of hundreds of thousands of stars...</i>

122
00:11:17,343 --> 00:11:20,017
<i>...according to the
scheme that she devised.</i>

123
00:11:20,180 --> 00:11:24,185
<i>Cannon discovered that the stars fell
into a continuous sequence...</i>

124
00:11:24,350 --> 00:11:28,981
<i>...of seven broad categories according
to their spectral line patterns.</i>

125
00:11:29,147 --> 00:11:31,366
<i>Each was designated by a letter.</i>

126
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:35,074
<i>But the spectral lines of two stars
in the same letter class...</i>

127
00:11:35,236 --> 00:11:37,159
<i>...could differ in subtle ways...</i>

128
00:11:37,322 --> 00:11:41,577
<i>...minute variations that Cannon learned
to recognize from memory.</i>

129
00:11:41,743 --> 00:11:43,996
<i>To distinguish these spectra
from one another...</i>

130
00:11:44,162 --> 00:11:48,542
<i>...she assigned ten numerical subcategories
for each class.</i>

131
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:51,177
Annie Jump Cannon organized the stars...

132
00:11:51,336 --> 00:11:55,967
...but it would fall to another scientist
to decipher the hidden meaning in her work.

133
00:11:58,426 --> 00:12:01,190
<i>In the England of 1923,
women were forbidden</i>

134
00:12:01,202 --> 00:12:03,978
<i>from pursuing advanced
degrees in science.</i>

135
00:12:04,140 --> 00:12:06,859
<i>But Cecilia Payne
had attended a lecture in London...</i>

136
00:12:07,018 --> 00:12:09,271
<i>...by the astronomer Sir
Arthur Eddington...</i>

137
00:12:09,437 --> 00:12:11,531
<i>...the first scientist
to provide evidence...</i>

138
00:12:11,689 --> 00:12:15,739
<i>...that Einstein's revolutionary
General Theory of Relativity was correct.</i>

139
00:12:15,902 --> 00:12:18,706
<i>From that moment on,
she knew that nothing</i>

140
00:12:18,718 --> 00:12:21,534
<i>would deter her from
pursuing her big dreams.</i>

141
00:12:22,825 --> 00:12:25,294
<i>She resolved to emigrate to America...</i>

142
00:12:25,453 --> 00:12:29,674
<i>...where women had already gained
the freedom to study the stars.</i>

143
00:12:29,832 --> 00:12:32,631
<i>Her application was accepted at Harvard.</i>

144
00:12:32,794 --> 00:12:34,341
<i>What she would discover there...</i>

145
00:12:34,504 --> 00:12:37,257
<i>...would challenge one of the
central beliefs of astronomy.</i>

146
00:12:38,132 --> 00:12:43,684
<i>The resulting impact would be the dawn
of modern astrophysics.</i>

147
00:12:52,647 --> 00:12:53,944
<i>TYSON".
As the decades passed...</i>

148
00:12:54,107 --> 00:12:57,611
<i>...Annie Jump Cannon and her team
kept sifting the stars...</i>

149
00:12:57,777 --> 00:13:01,281
<i>...checking each one's spectral signature
with a fleeting glance...</i>

150
00:13:01,447 --> 00:13:04,121
<i>...and then dropping them
into one of seven categories.</i>

151
00:13:04,284 --> 00:13:08,255
<i>They became hundreds of thousands of dots
in a larger picture...</i>

152
00:13:08,413 --> 00:13:10,290
<i>...which no one could yet understand.</i>

153
00:13:11,291 --> 00:13:15,216
<i>Into this community of women
came one more.</i>

154
00:13:16,713 --> 00:13:18,306
Well, hello there.

155
00:13:19,173 --> 00:13:21,301
You must be Miss Payne.

156
00:13:21,467 --> 00:13:23,435
We've been waiting for you.

157
00:13:23,594 --> 00:13:24,971
Come on in.

158
00:13:25,138 --> 00:13:27,857
<i>TYSON: Cecilia Payne
had never experienced such kindness...</i>

159
00:13:28,016 --> 00:13:30,235
<i>...in a scientific setting before.</i>

160
00:13:30,393 --> 00:13:34,944
<i>This sisterhood generously shared the
fruits of their labors with her...</i>

161
00:13:35,106 --> 00:13:40,408
<i>...and she turned their observations into
a radical new understanding of the stars.</i>

162
00:13:40,903 --> 00:13:43,122
The two women became great friends.

163
00:13:43,281 --> 00:13:46,581
Cannon taught Payne everything
she had learned about stellar spectra.

164
00:13:46,743 --> 00:13:49,087
And Payne began
to analyze Cannon's data...

165
00:13:49,245 --> 00:13:52,340
...to see if she could determine
the actual chemical composition...

166
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:54,626
...and physical state of the stars.

167
00:13:54,792 --> 00:13:58,763
She brought to this work her expertise
in theoretical and atomic physics.

168
00:14:01,549 --> 00:14:04,268
<i>The most prominent features
in the spectra of stars...</i>

169
00:14:04,427 --> 00:14:08,227
<i>...showed the presence of heavy elements
such as calcium...</i>

170
00:14:08,848 --> 00:14:13,103
<i>...and iron, which are among
the most abundant elements in the Earth.</i>

171
00:14:13,269 --> 00:14:16,489
So astronomers naturally concluded
that the stars...

172
00:14:16,647 --> 00:14:21,118
...were made of the same elements as the
Earth and in roughly the same proportions.

173
00:14:22,153 --> 00:14:27,455
<i>In 1924, Henry Norris Russell
was the dean of American astronomers...</i>

174
00:14:27,617 --> 00:14:31,338
<i>...having made major contributions
to our understanding of the stars.</i>

175
00:14:31,496 --> 00:14:36,377
RUSSELL: Forty to 45 of the chemical
elements that we have here on Earth...

176
00:14:36,542 --> 00:14:39,466
...are also present
in the spectrum of the sun.

177
00:14:39,629 --> 00:14:45,557
So we can assume that the composition
of the sun resembles that of the Earth.

178
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:49,439
If one were to heat the crust of the Earth
toincandescence“.

179
00:14:49,597 --> 00:14:52,646
...its spectrum would resemble that
of the sun.

180
00:14:52,809 --> 00:14:54,982
[MURMURING]

181
00:15:07,281 --> 00:15:11,161
Annie, I think I now understand
what it all means.

182
00:15:11,327 --> 00:15:13,170
All your years of work.

183
00:15:13,329 --> 00:15:14,330
Tell me.

184
00:15:14,497 --> 00:15:16,920
I've calculated what the spectra
should look like...

185
00:15:17,083 --> 00:15:19,051
...across a wide range
of temperatures...

186
00:15:19,210 --> 00:15:22,680
...and they match your system
of classification perfectly.

187
00:15:22,839 --> 00:15:26,810
The spectrum of any star
tells you exactly how hot it is.

188
00:15:26,968 --> 00:15:33,066
Your "O-B-A-F-G-K-M" is really a
temperature scale of the stars...

189
00:15:33,224 --> 00:15:35,318
...from the hottest to the coldest.

190
00:15:37,645 --> 00:15:38,897
Here's the headline, Annie.

191
00:15:39,063 --> 00:15:41,532
Thanks to your work,
I've discovered that the stars...

192
00:15:41,691 --> 00:15:44,035
...are made almost entirely
of hydrogen and helium.

193
00:15:44,193 --> 00:15:49,199
There's a million times more hydrogen
and helium than the metals in the stars.

194
00:15:49,365 --> 00:15:51,993
I know, it sounds daft.

195
00:15:52,785 --> 00:15:54,662
Are you certain?

196
00:15:54,829 --> 00:15:58,709
Has anyone else checked
your calculations?

197
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:00,877
Not yet, but it's all in my thesis...

198
00:16:01,043 --> 00:16:03,842
...which is already on its way
to Professor Russell.

199
00:16:15,683 --> 00:16:17,526
Poor woman.

200
00:16:17,685 --> 00:16:20,529
<i>TYSON".
Russell felt sorry for Cecilia Payne.</i>

201
00:16:20,688 --> 00:16:25,159
<i>Her thesis appeared to him
to be fundamentally flawed.</i>

202
00:16:32,033 --> 00:16:34,377
<i>RUSSELL".
It is clearly impossible that hydrogen...</i>

203
00:16:34,535 --> 00:16:38,381
<i>...should be a million times more abundant
than the metals.</i>

204
00:16:43,127 --> 00:16:45,852
<i>TYSON: Her carefully
gathered evidence flew in</i>

205
00:16:45,864 --> 00:16:48,600
<i>the face of conventional
scientific wisdom.</i>

206
00:16:48,758 --> 00:16:51,261
<i>"How could I be right," she asked...</i>

207
00:16:51,427 --> 00:16:57,230
<i>..."if that must mean that
such a distinguished scientist was wrong?"</i>

208
00:16:57,391 --> 00:17:00,520
<i>Despite her confidence
in the quality of her research...</i>

209
00:17:00,686 --> 00:17:03,701
<i>...she caved and added
a sentence to her</i>

210
00:17:03,713 --> 00:17:06,739
<i>thesis that undermined
its greatest insight.</i>

211
00:17:12,532 --> 00:17:16,628
It would be four years before Russell
realized that Payne was right.

212
00:17:16,786 --> 00:17:21,963
To his credit, as soon as he did,
he acknowledged that it was her discovery.

213
00:17:26,337 --> 00:17:29,136
<i>Payne's "Stellar Atmospheres"
is widely regarded...</i>

214
00:17:29,298 --> 00:17:33,144
<i>...as the most brilliant PhD thesis
ever written in astronomy.</i>

215
00:17:33,302 --> 00:17:36,681
<i>It became the standard text in its field.</i>

216
00:17:38,474 --> 00:17:41,648
<i>PAYNE: I was to blame
for not having pressed my point.</i>

217
00:17:41,811 --> 00:17:46,191
<i>I had given in to authority
when I believed I was right.</i>

218
00:17:46,357 --> 00:17:51,158
<i>If you are sure of your facts,
you should defend your position.</i>

219
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:54,667
TYSON: The words of the
powerful may prevail

220
00:17:54,679 --> 00:17:56,994
in other spheres of
human experience...

221
00:17:57,159 --> 00:17:59,958
...but in science,
the only thing that counts...

222
00:18:00,121 --> 00:18:03,500
...is the evidence
and the logic of the argument itself.

223
00:18:03,666 --> 00:18:05,259
Cecilia Payne's interpretation...

224
00:18:05,418 --> 00:18:08,217
...of Annie Jump Cannon's sequence
of stellar spectra...

225
00:18:08,379 --> 00:18:12,384
...made it possible for us
to read the life stories of the stars...

226
00:18:12,550 --> 00:18:16,003
...and to trace the story
of life itself back

227
00:18:16,015 --> 00:18:19,479
to its beginnings in
their fiery deaths.

228
00:18:28,441 --> 00:18:30,910
<i>TYSON".
There are many kinds of stars.</i>

229
00:18:31,277 --> 00:18:33,530
<i>Some are bright like the sun.</i>

230
00:18:33,696 --> 00:18:35,369
<i>Some are dim.</i>

231
00:18:35,531 --> 00:18:40,037
<i>The greatest stars are ten million
times larger than the smallest ones.</i>

232
00:18:40,328 --> 00:18:45,585
<i>Some stars are old beyond imagining,
more than ten billion years of age.</i>

233
00:18:46,208 --> 00:18:48,302
<i>Others are being born right now.</i>

234
00:18:52,548 --> 00:18:56,769
When atoms fuse in the hearts of stars,
they make starlight.

235
00:18:56,927 --> 00:18:58,224
Stars are born in litters...

236
00:18:58,387 --> 00:19:02,062
<i>...formed from the gas and dust
of interstellar clouds.</i>

237
00:19:02,224 --> 00:19:06,570
<i>The mass of the individual stars in
a litter can range from the runts--</i>

238
00:19:06,729 --> 00:19:08,902
<i>Not much larger than the largest planets.</i>

239
00:19:09,065 --> 00:19:12,069
<i>--to the supergiant stars
that dwarf the sun.</i>

240
00:19:18,532 --> 00:19:22,207
The stars in the nebula below Orion's Belt
are newborns...

241
00:19:22,370 --> 00:19:24,543
...around five million years old...

242
00:19:24,705 --> 00:19:29,256
...and still swaddled in the gas and dust
that gave birth to them.

243
00:19:29,710 --> 00:19:34,557
<i>The stars in the Pleiades are already
toddlers, about 100 million years old.</i>

244
00:19:34,715 --> 00:19:37,059
<i>They've shed their blankets
of gas and dust...</i>

245
00:19:37,218 --> 00:19:40,347
<i>...but they're still bound together
by their mutual gravity.</i>

246
00:19:40,513 --> 00:19:42,186
<i>Another few hundred million years...</i>

247
00:19:42,348 --> 00:19:45,227
<i>...and they'll drift apart
and go their separate ways...</i>

248
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:47,441
...never <i>to</i> meet again.

249
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:51,149
<i>Most of the stars of the Big Dipper
are adolescents...</i>

250
00:19:51,315 --> 00:19:53,443
<i>...roughly a half a billion years old.</i>

251
00:19:53,609 --> 00:19:56,237
<i>They've already drifted apart
from their birth cluster...</i>

252
00:19:56,404 --> 00:19:59,123
<i>...although we can still trace
their common ancestry.</i>

253
00:19:59,281 --> 00:20:03,286
<i>Eventually, they'll spread out
around the Milky Way galaxy.</i>

254
00:20:03,452 --> 00:20:08,800
<i>But most of the familiar constellations
are a mix of entirely unrelated stars...</i>

255
00:20:08,958 --> 00:20:13,589
<i>...some faint and nearby,
others bright and far away.</i>

256
00:20:16,674 --> 00:20:18,221
<i>Our own sun?</i>

257
00:20:18,384 --> 00:20:20,682
From the distance of even a few
light-years...

258
00:20:20,845 --> 00:20:23,439
...it's hard to find amidst
the other stars.

259
00:20:23,973 --> 00:20:25,395
It's that one.

260
00:20:27,435 --> 00:20:30,689
Our sun is middle-aged and
a long way from where it was born.

261
00:20:30,855 --> 00:20:34,109
Its sister stars, hatched from
the same interstellar cloud...

262
00:20:34,275 --> 00:20:36,824
...are dispersed throughout
the galaxy.

263
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,164
Many of them have
their own planets.

264
00:20:40,322 --> 00:20:44,623
Perhaps some of them nurture
the evolution of life and intelligence.

265
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:47,781
Most of the stars in
our night sky actually

266
00:20:47,793 --> 00:20:50,341
orbit around one or more
stellar companions.

267
00:20:50,499 --> 00:20:53,378
With the naked eye, we usually
can't see the fainter members...

268
00:20:53,544 --> 00:20:55,797
...in such double
and multiple star systems.

269
00:20:58,674 --> 00:21:02,053
<i>TYSON: On</i> a <i>world with three suns,
the nights would be rare...</i>

270
00:21:02,219 --> 00:21:06,440
<i>...and the days might alternate
between red and blue.</i>

271
00:21:12,688 --> 00:21:15,362
<i>It is the destiny of stars to collapse.</i>

272
00:21:16,025 --> 00:21:19,325
<i>Of the thousands of stars you see
when you look up at the night sky...</i>

273
00:21:19,487 --> 00:21:23,117
<i>...every one of them is living in
an interval between two collapses:</i>

274
00:21:23,282 --> 00:21:27,628
<i>An initial collapse of a dark,
interstellar gas cloud to form the star...</i>

275
00:21:27,787 --> 00:21:32,839
<i>...and a final collapse of the luminous
star on its way to its ultimate fate.</i>

276
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:37,005
Gravity makes stars contract,
unless some other force intervenes.

277
00:21:37,171 --> 00:21:40,926
The sun is a great big ball
of incandescent gas.

278
00:21:41,091 --> 00:21:45,597
The super-hot gas in its core pushes
the sun to expand outward.

279
00:21:45,763 --> 00:21:49,939
At the same time, the sun's own gravity
pulls it inward to contract.

280
00:21:50,100 --> 00:21:54,606
And our sun is poised between
these two forces in a stable equilibrium...

281
00:21:54,772 --> 00:21:57,776
...between gravity and nuclear fire.

282
00:21:57,942 --> 00:22:01,697
A balance it will maintain
for another 4 billion years.

283
00:22:01,862 --> 00:22:07,244
But as the sun consumes hydrogen,
its core very slowly shrinks...

284
00:22:07,409 --> 00:22:10,629
...and the sun's surface gradually expands
in response.

285
00:22:10,788 --> 00:22:15,168
It happens very slowly, imperceptibly,
over the course of millions of years.

286
00:22:15,334 --> 00:22:21,512
But in about a billion years, the sun will
be 1O percent brighter than it is today.

287
00:22:24,051 --> 00:22:26,838
Ten percent may not sound
like much, but that

288
00:22:26,850 --> 00:22:29,649
extra heat will have a
big effect on Earth.

289
00:22:36,981 --> 00:22:42,329
When the sun finally exhausts its nuclear
fuel 4 or 5 billion years from now...

290
00:22:42,486 --> 00:22:46,207
...its gas will cool and
the pressure will fall.

291
00:22:46,657 --> 00:22:50,457
The sun's interior can no longer support
the weight of the outer layers...

292
00:22:50,619 --> 00:22:53,793
...and the initial collapse will resume.

293
00:22:54,373 --> 00:22:56,467
Nothing lasts forever.

294
00:22:56,625 --> 00:22:58,627
Even the stars die.

295
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:04,972
Helium, the ash of 10 billion years of
hydrogen fusion, has built up in the core.

296
00:23:05,134 --> 00:23:08,559
With no nuclear fire to sustain its weight,
the core collapses...

297
00:23:08,721 --> 00:23:13,477
...until it becomes hot enough to start
fusing helium into carbon and oxygen.

298
00:23:13,642 --> 00:23:17,692
The core of the sun is now much hotter
than it was before.

299
00:23:17,855 --> 00:23:19,983
Its atmosphere rapidly expands.

300
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:22,948
Over the next billion years,
it'll become bloated...

301
00:23:23,110 --> 00:23:28,867
...to more than 100 times
its original size, a red giant star.

302
00:23:32,161 --> 00:23:36,667
<i>It will envelop and devour
the planets Mercury...</i>

303
00:23:39,335 --> 00:23:41,633
<i>...and Venus...</i>

304
00:23:45,591 --> 00:23:48,595
<i>...and possibly the Earth.</i>

305
00:23:50,012 --> 00:23:54,483
<i>I like to think that tens of millions of
years before that far distant future...</i>

306
00:23:54,642 --> 00:24:00,900
<i>...if there still be life born of Earth, it
will have found new homes among the stars.</i>

307
00:24:03,192 --> 00:24:07,618
<i>Once the sun burns through its helium,
it will become highly unstable...</i>

308
00:24:07,780 --> 00:24:11,034
<i>...casting off its outer layers into space.</i>

309
00:24:12,701 --> 00:24:14,624
<i>The exposed, super-hot core...</i>

310
00:24:14,787 --> 00:24:18,883
<i>...will flood its surroundings
with high-energy ultraviolet light.</i>

311
00:24:21,085 --> 00:24:25,386
<i>The atoms will perform a wild,
fluorescent dance.</i>

312
00:24:31,261 --> 00:24:34,048
The sun will collapse
like a souffle, shrinking

313
00:24:34,060 --> 00:24:36,859
a hundredfold to the
size of the Earth.

314
00:24:37,017 --> 00:24:39,611
And at that point, the
sun will be so dense...

315
00:24:39,770 --> 00:24:44,822
...that its overcrowded electrons will push
back, stopping any further contraction.

316
00:24:44,984 --> 00:24:50,081
The kernel of light at the center will be
the only part of the sun that endures...

317
00:24:50,239 --> 00:24:53,106
...a white dwarf star
that will go on shining

318
00:24:53,118 --> 00:24:55,996
dimly for another
100 billion years.

319
00:24:56,161 --> 00:25:00,758
Will the beings of a distant future,
sailing past this wreck of a star...

320
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:05,797
...have any idea of the life and worlds
that it once warmed?

321
00:25:29,153 --> 00:25:33,579
<i>TYSON: The psychedelic death shrouds
of ordinary stars are ﬂeeting...</i>

322
00:25:35,200 --> 00:25:37,669
<i>...lasting only tens of thousands
of years...</i>

323
00:25:37,828 --> 00:25:40,445
<i>...before dissipating
in the interstellar gas</i>

324
00:25:40,457 --> 00:25:43,085
<i>and dust from which the
new stars will be born.</i>

325
00:25:48,047 --> 00:25:52,143
<i>The stars in a binary star system
can have a different fate.</i>

326
00:25:52,634 --> 00:25:57,731
<i>Sirius, the brightest star in the night
sky, has a very faint stellar companion...</i>

327
00:25:57,890 --> 00:25:59,563
...a <i>white</i> dwarf.

328
00:25:59,725 --> 00:26:02,103
<i>It was once a sun-like star.</i>

329
00:26:02,269 --> 00:26:06,024
<i>Someday, when Sirius runs out of fuel
and becomes a red giant...</i>

330
00:26:06,190 --> 00:26:09,114
<i>...it will shed its substance
onto the white dwarf.</i>

331
00:26:10,319 --> 00:26:13,169
<i>The intense gravity of the
companion will attract</i>

332
00:26:13,181 --> 00:26:16,042
<i>that gas, pulling it
into a spiraling disk.</i>

333
00:26:16,200 --> 00:26:20,250
<i>When the gas from the larger star falls
onto the surface of the white dwarf...</i>

334
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:23,666
<i>...it will trigger nuclear explosions.</i>

335
00:26:27,419 --> 00:26:32,141
<i>The greatest burst will release 100,000
times more energy than the sun.</i>

336
00:26:32,299 --> 00:26:36,805
<i>Each one of those star bursts
is called a "nova"...</i>

337
00:26:36,970 --> 00:26:39,974
<i>...from the Latin for "new."</i>

338
00:26:40,140 --> 00:26:44,566
A star about 15 times as massive
as the sun, one like Rigel...

339
00:26:44,728 --> 00:26:47,327
...the blue supergiant
that forms the right

340
00:26:47,339 --> 00:26:49,950
foot of Orion, has a
different fate in store.

341
00:26:50,109 --> 00:26:53,363
Its collapse will not be stopped
by the pressure of electrons.

342
00:26:55,447 --> 00:26:58,291
The star will keep falling in on itself...

343
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:03,711
...until its nuclei become so overcrowded
that they push back.

344
00:27:06,708 --> 00:27:09,928
Rigel will shrink down
about 100,000 times...

345
00:27:10,087 --> 00:27:15,218
...until there's no space left between
the nuclei and it can shrink no more.

346
00:27:19,888 --> 00:27:25,395
At that point, it ignites a more powerful
nuclear reaction: A supernova.

347
00:27:30,899 --> 00:27:34,574
Most stellar evolution takes millions
or billions of years.

348
00:27:34,736 --> 00:27:39,082
But the interior collapse that triggers
a supernova explosion takes only seconds.

349
00:27:39,741 --> 00:27:44,588
What remains will be an atomic nucleus
the size of a small city...

350
00:27:44,746 --> 00:27:49,172
...a rapidly rotating
neutron star called a pulsar.

351
00:28:01,763 --> 00:28:05,188
<i>But for a star more than 30 times
as massive as the sun...</i>

352
00:28:05,350 --> 00:28:11,153
...a <i>star like Alnilam in Orion's Belt,
there will be no stopping its collapse.</i>

353
00:28:11,315 --> 00:28:16,867
<i>In a few million years, when Alnilam runs
out of fuel, it, too, will go supernova.</i>

354
00:28:17,029 --> 00:28:22,081
<i>The imploding core of Alnilam
will be so massive...</i>

355
00:28:22,242 --> 00:28:26,793
<i>...that not even nuclear forces will be
strong enough to hold off its collapse.</i>

356
00:28:26,955 --> 00:28:29,299
<i>Nothing can withstand such gravity.</i>

357
00:28:29,458 --> 00:28:32,962
<i>And such a star has an astonishing destiny.</i>

358
00:28:36,882 --> 00:28:41,137
<i>It will continue to collapse,
crossing a boundary in space-time...</i>

359
00:28:41,303 --> 00:28:45,558
<i>...called the "event horizon,"
beyond which we cannot see.</i>

360
00:28:46,475 --> 00:28:50,981
<i>When it traverses that frontier,
the star will vanish completely from sight.</i>

361
00:28:52,981 --> 00:28:57,657
<i>It will be inside a black hole,
a place where gravity is so strong...</i>

362
00:28:57,819 --> 00:29:01,449
<i>...that nothing, not
even light, can escape.</i>

363
00:29:06,995 --> 00:29:11,000
But there's an even more dramatic fate
that awaits a rare kind of star.

364
00:29:11,166 --> 00:29:12,918
There's one of them in our galaxy.

365
00:29:13,085 --> 00:29:19,092
It's so unstable that when it goes,
it won't become a mere nova or supernova.

366
00:29:19,258 --> 00:29:24,059
It'll become something far more
catastrophic: A hypernova.

367
00:29:24,346 --> 00:29:26,690
And it could happen in our lifetime.

368
00:29:37,609 --> 00:29:41,489
<i>TYSON: There are few places on Earth
to get a better view of the night sky...</i>

369
00:29:41,655 --> 00:29:44,249
<i>...than the Australian Outback.</i>

370
00:29:45,867 --> 00:29:52,625
No buildings, no cars, streetlights,
nothing out here, just lots of starlight.

371
00:29:52,791 --> 00:29:54,964
And the occasional kangaroo.

372
00:29:55,127 --> 00:29:58,347
You can get a particularly good view
of the Milky Way from down here.

373
00:29:58,505 --> 00:30:04,137
The center of our galaxy rises high in the
sky, and it arches across the heavens...

374
00:30:04,303 --> 00:30:06,476
...like the backbone of night.

375
00:30:06,638 --> 00:30:08,481
<i>We live in a spiral galaxy.</i>

376
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:10,267
<i>And when we look at the Milky Way...</i>

377
00:30:10,434 --> 00:30:14,280
<i>...we're seeing light from billions
of stars in its spiral disk.</i>

378
00:30:14,438 --> 00:30:17,493
<i>And under this beautiful
dark sky, you can see</i>

379
00:30:17,505 --> 00:30:20,571
<i>that the Milky Way isn't
a uniform band of light.</i>

380
00:30:20,736 --> 00:30:23,740
<i>There are dark patches,
breaks in the starlight.</i>

381
00:30:23,905 --> 00:30:27,330
<i>Those dark patches
are caused by interstellar dust.</i>

382
00:30:27,492 --> 00:30:31,042
<i>The dust blocks the starlight,
and there's lots of it.</i>

383
00:30:32,497 --> 00:30:36,343
<i>Most cultures looked up at the stars
and connected the dots...</i>

384
00:30:36,501 --> 00:30:38,845
<i>...to form familiar images in the sky.</i>

385
00:30:39,004 --> 00:30:41,052
<i>Constellations.</i>

386
00:30:46,345 --> 00:30:50,691
But the Aboriginal people of Australia
saw a pattern in the darkness...

387
00:30:50,849 --> 00:30:52,817
...running through the Milky Way.

388
00:30:52,976 --> 00:30:57,903
They saw an emu,
a large bird native to this continent.

389
00:30:58,065 --> 00:31:01,945
<i>Not in the stars,
but in the absence of stars.</i>

390
00:31:04,905 --> 00:31:07,408
There are so many ways
to look at the night sky.

391
00:31:07,574 --> 00:31:10,453
For a million years or more,
we've watched the sky.

392
00:31:10,619 --> 00:31:12,246
And a lot's happened in that time.

393
00:31:12,412 --> 00:31:16,292
Supernova explode in our galaxy
about once a century.

394
00:31:16,458 --> 00:31:21,385
If we could compress all those nights
of stargazing into a single minute...

395
00:31:21,546 --> 00:31:24,425
...this is what we would see.

396
00:31:29,012 --> 00:31:30,685
Now, if our eyes were telescopes...

397
00:31:30,847 --> 00:31:33,817
...if they were light buckets
as big as wagon wheels...

398
00:31:33,975 --> 00:31:37,149
...and our vision was not limited
to just one kind of light...

399
00:31:37,312 --> 00:31:40,316
...then this is the Milky Way
we would see.

400
00:31:42,442 --> 00:31:46,663
<i>A galaxy in near-infrared light
with streaming tendrils of dust...</i>

401
00:31:46,822 --> 00:31:49,496
<i>...hurled outward by those
exploding supernovas...</i>

402
00:31:49,658 --> 00:31:53,413
<i>...silhouetted against a backdrop
of countless stars.</i>

403
00:31:54,871 --> 00:31:59,172
About 7500 light-years away,
in another part of our galaxy...

404
00:31:59,334 --> 00:32:04,010
<i>...there is a place of upheaval
on an inconceivable scale.</i>

405
00:32:12,681 --> 00:32:15,901
<i>TYSON".
This is the Carina Nebula.</i>

406
00:32:16,059 --> 00:32:18,983
<i>A star-making machine.</i>

407
00:32:22,899 --> 00:32:26,699
<i>It takes</i> a <i>ray of light
50 years to cross it.</i>

408
00:32:30,157 --> 00:32:34,754
<i>The titanic stars born here
sear the surrounding gas and dust...</i>

409
00:32:34,911 --> 00:32:37,790
<i>...with their fierce ultraviolet radiation.</i>

410
00:32:38,832 --> 00:32:43,713
<i>When a massive star dies,
it blows itself to smithereens.</i>

411
00:32:46,381 --> 00:32:49,260
<i>Its substance is propelled
across the vastness...</i>

412
00:32:49,426 --> 00:32:52,976
<i>...to be stirred by starlight
and gathered up by gravity.</i>

413
00:32:53,555 --> 00:32:57,605
<i>Stars to dust and dust to stars.</i>

414
00:32:58,185 --> 00:33:01,234
<i>In the cosmos, nothing is wasted.</i>

415
00:33:03,273 --> 00:33:07,278
<i>But there's an upper limit
