00:33:49,778 --> 00:33:53,533
<i>...and pouring out 5
million times more light.</i>

427
00:33:53,698 --> 00:33:57,703
<i>It's pushing the upper limit
of what a star can be.</i>

428
00:33:58,828 --> 00:34:01,154
<i>What's more, there's
evidence that Eta Carinae</i>

429
00:34:01,166 --> 00:34:03,504
<i>is being gravitationally
tormented...</i>

430
00:34:03,667 --> 00:34:05,385
...by an <i>evil</i> twin...

431
00:34:05,544 --> 00:34:11,597
<i>...another massive star in orbit around it
as close as Saturn is to the sun.</i>

432
00:34:12,300 --> 00:34:15,975
<i>The core of a supermassive star
pours out so much light...</i>

433
00:34:16,137 --> 00:34:20,108
<i>...that the outward pressure can overwhelm
the star's gravity.</i>

434
00:34:20,267 --> 00:34:24,773
<i>If a star is too massive, its radiation
pressure overpowers its gravity...</i>

435
00:34:24,938 --> 00:34:27,282
<i>...and blows the star apart.</i>

436
00:34:29,317 --> 00:34:33,914
The fate of Eta Carinae was sealed
when it was born millions of years ago.

437
00:34:34,072 --> 00:34:38,498
When it finally does blow up--
And who knows, maybe it already has...

438
00:34:38,660 --> 00:34:43,291
...after all we're looking at it by light
that left the star 7500 years ago.

439
00:34:43,456 --> 00:34:47,632
--It will be a cataclysm
unlike anything we've seen before.

440
00:34:48,003 --> 00:34:49,175
A hypernova.

441
00:35:01,516 --> 00:35:04,019
<i>An explosion so powerful,
it'll make a supernova...</i>

442
00:35:04,185 --> 00:35:06,938
<i>...seem like a firecracker by comparison.</i>

443
00:35:07,689 --> 00:35:10,431
<i>If there are nearby solar
systems with planets</i>

444
00:35:10,443 --> 00:35:13,196
<i>harboring life, their
days are numbered.</i>

445
00:35:13,695 --> 00:35:17,165
A hypernova spews
so much radiation into space...

446
00:35:17,324 --> 00:35:20,328
...not just light, but
x-rays and gamma rays...

447
00:35:20,493 --> 00:35:24,623
...that planets that are dozens,
or perhaps hundreds of light-years away...

448
00:35:24,789 --> 00:35:29,465
...could be stripped of their atmospheres
and bathed in deadly radiation.

449
00:35:29,628 --> 00:35:33,508
It would wreak havoc in thousands
of nearby star systems.

450
00:35:34,424 --> 00:35:36,893
Right about now,
you're probably asking yourself:

451
00:35:37,052 --> 00:35:38,599
"Are we safe?"

452
00:35:39,054 --> 00:35:43,651
If Eta Carinae blows up,
what happens to Earth?

453
00:35:44,225 --> 00:35:47,104
<i>Rest assured, Earth will be just fine.</i>

454
00:35:47,270 --> 00:35:50,900
<i>Remember, we're 7500 light-years away
from Eta Carinae.</i>

455
00:35:51,066 --> 00:35:54,246
<i>The intensity of radiation
from a star, even an</i>

456
00:35:54,258 --> 00:35:57,449
<i>exploding star, falls off
rapidly with distance.</i>

457
00:35:57,614 --> 00:36:02,415
<i>But still, Eta Carinae in its death throes
will put on quite a show.</i>

458
00:36:02,577 --> 00:36:05,205
<i>It will light up the night
of the southern hemisphere...</i>

459
00:36:05,372 --> 00:36:07,215
<i>...with the brightness of a second moon.</i>

460
00:36:07,374 --> 00:36:11,720
<i>The most dramatic swan song
a star can sing.</i>

461
00:36:17,926 --> 00:36:20,645
<i>TYSON".
Our ancestors worshiped the sun.</i>

462
00:36:20,970 --> 00:36:22,893
<i>And they were far from foolish.</i>

463
00:36:23,932 --> 00:36:29,484
It makes good sense to revere the sun
and stars, because we are their children.

464
00:36:29,646 --> 00:36:34,652
The silicon in the rocks, the oxygen
in the air, the carbon in our DNA...

465
00:36:34,818 --> 00:36:38,539
...the iron in our skyscrapers,
the silver in ourjewelry...

466
00:36:38,697 --> 00:36:42,622
...were all made in stars
billions of years ago.

467
00:36:42,784 --> 00:36:48,712
Our planet, our society,
and we ourselves are stardust.

468
00:36:50,500 --> 00:36:53,424
Well, what is it that
makes the atoms dance?

469
00:36:53,586 --> 00:36:59,389
How is the energy of a star transformed
into everything that happens in the world?

470
00:37:00,009 --> 00:37:03,479
What is energy? We're awash in it.

471
00:37:03,638 --> 00:37:07,984
When hydrogen atoms fuse inside the sun,
they make helium atoms.

472
00:37:08,143 --> 00:37:10,396
And this fusion emits a burst of energy...

473
00:37:10,562 --> 00:37:13,491
...that can wander inside
the sun for 1O million

474
00:37:13,503 --> 00:37:16,444
years before making its
way to the surface.

475
00:37:16,609 --> 00:37:23,037
And once there, it's free to fly straight
from the sun to the Earth as visible light.

476
00:37:23,992 --> 00:37:26,529
If it should strike the
surface of a leaf, it

477
00:37:26,541 --> 00:37:29,089
will be stored in the
plant as chemical energy.

478
00:37:30,331 --> 00:37:31,958
Sunshine...

479
00:37:32,292 --> 00:37:33,509
...into moonshine.

480
00:37:44,220 --> 00:37:46,348
[BOTH SPEAK IN ITALIAN]

481
00:37:53,062 --> 00:37:56,692
I can feel my brain turning
the chemical energy of the wine...

482
00:37:56,858 --> 00:37:59,031
...into the electrical
energy of my thoughts...

483
00:37:59,194 --> 00:38:03,665
...and directing my vocal chords to produce
the acoustic energy of my voice.

484
00:38:04,032 --> 00:38:08,378
Such transformations of energy
are happening everywhere all the time.

485
00:38:08,870 --> 00:38:13,876
Energy from our star drives the wind
and the waves and the life around us.

486
00:38:14,042 --> 00:38:17,797
How lucky we are to have this vast source
of clean energy...

487
00:38:17,962 --> 00:38:21,091
...falling like manna from heaven
on all of us.

488
00:38:22,008 --> 00:38:26,730
To Annie Jump Cannon,
Henrietta Swan Leavitt and Cecilia Payne...

489
00:38:26,888 --> 00:38:30,233
...for blazing the trail
to modern astrophysics.

490
00:38:30,391 --> 00:38:33,270
And to all the sisters of the sun.

491
00:38:39,567 --> 00:38:43,413
<i>TYSON". There's no refuge
from change in the cosmos.</i>

492
00:38:44,072 --> 00:38:46,621
Some 10 or 2O million years from now...

493
00:38:46,783 --> 00:38:49,673
...it'll seem for a
cosmic moment as if Orion

494
00:38:49,685 --> 00:38:52,586
is finally about to catch
the seven sisters.

495
00:38:53,039 --> 00:38:58,796
But before he has them in his clutches, the
biggest stars of Orion will go supernova.

496
00:38:58,962 --> 00:39:02,182
Orion's pursuit of the Pleiades
will finally end...

497
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:05,377
...and the seven sisters
will glide serenely

498
00:39:05,389 --> 00:39:08,438
into the waiting arms
of the Milky Way.

499
00:39:11,558 --> 00:39:17,281
<i>We on Earth marvel, and rightly so,
at the return of our solitary sun.</i>

500
00:39:17,438 --> 00:39:21,033
<i>But from a planet orbiting a star
in a distant globular cluster...</i>

501
00:39:21,192 --> 00:39:24,492
<i>...a still more glorious dawn awaits.</i>

502
00:39:25,572 --> 00:39:27,415
<i>Not a sunrise...</i>

503
00:39:28,449 --> 00:39:30,622
<i>...but a galaxy rise.</i>

504
00:39:30,785 --> 00:39:35,006
<i>A morning filled with 200 billion suns.</i>

505
00:39:35,164 --> 00:39:38,293
<i>The rising of the Milky Way.</i>

506
00:39:38,459 --> 00:39:42,089
<i>An enormous spiral form
with collapsing gas clouds...</i>

507
00:39:42,255 --> 00:39:45,850
<i>...condensing planetary systems,
luminous supergiants...</i>

508
00:39:46,009 --> 00:39:47,886
<i>...stable middle-aged suns...</i>

509
00:39:48,052 --> 00:39:50,976
<i>...red giants, white dwarfs,
planetary nebulae...</i>

510
00:39:51,139 --> 00:39:55,064
<i>...supernovas, neutron stars, pulsars,
black holes.</i>

511
00:39:55,226 --> 00:39:58,343
<i>And, there is every
reason to think, other</i>

512
00:39:58,355 --> 00:40:01,484
<i>exotic objects that we
have yet to discover.</i>

513
00:40:01,649 --> 00:40:05,199
<i>From such a world,
high above the Milky Way...</i>

514
00:40:05,361 --> 00:40:10,162
<i>...it would be clear, as it is beginning
to be clear on our world...</i>

515
00:40:10,325 --> 00:40:14,171
<i>...that we are made by the atoms
and the stars...</i>

516
00:40:15,246 --> 00:40:20,719
<i>...that our matter and our form are forged
by the great and ancient cosmos...</i>

517
00:40:22,211 --> 00:40:24,839
<i>...of which we are a part.</i>

